<ResourceDictionary xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml/presentation"
                    xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml"
                    xmlns:sys="clr-namespace:System;assembly=mscorlib"
                    xmlns:po="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml/presentation/options">
    <!--
      Overrides for the vendored DsmSuite matrix (ThirdParty/DsmSuite). Everything the matrix draws is
      resolved by key through FindResource / StaticResource, so restyling it needs no change to their
      code at all: this dictionary is merged last in App.xaml and therefore wins.

      One constraint the values here have to respect: MatrixColor1..4 are not semantic —
      MatrixColorConverter.GetColor(depth) maps them to nesting depth. They should read as an ordered
      ramp, not as four unrelated colours.

      There used to be a second one: the hover and selected variants were built by multiplying the colour,
      so anything above roughly 210 clamped and stopped reacting. That is gone — the highlight is a fixed
      darkening now, see HighlightFactorHovered below — and colours here can be chosen freely.
    -->

    <!--
      Hover and selection crosshair. These are no longer multiplication factors but the number of channel
      steps the cell is darkened by - see MatrixTheme.GetHighlightBrush for why the multiplication was
      replaced. 26 and 45 are visible on every step of the ramp below and on the empty cell alike; the
      crossing cell gets both, so 71.
    -->
    <sys:Double x:Key="HighlightFactorHovered">26</sys:Double>
    <sys:Double x:Key="HighlightFactorSelected">45</sys:Double>

    <!-- Text. Near-black rather than pure black; less harsh against the light cells. -->
    <SolidColorBrush x:Key="TextColor" po:Freeze="True">#1F2933</SolidColorBrush>

    <!-- Empty cells. Light and neutral so that anything filled reads as foreground. -->
    <SolidColorBrush x:Key="MatrixColorBackground" po:Freeze="True">#E4E7EA</SolidColorBrush>

    <!--
      Nesting depth, 1..4. A single cool ramp that darkens with depth, so the eye reads "deeper" without
      a legend. The original four (#f1d9cf, #cfd1cc, #bab8b7, #ced3de) sat at nearly the same lightness
      in three different hues, which is why the levels were hard to tell apart.

      The range is wider than the cell weights would like. Black on #748C9E is 4.2:1, which is poor for a
      10px digit, and a narrower ramp (tried: #CDD6DE .. #9AA9B7, 6.1:1 at the deep end) does measurably
      better by that count. It was rejected anyway: the nested blocks stopped separating, and telling the
      levels apart is the whole job of these four colours. Contrast the digits can spare, structure they
      cannot - the tooltip carries the exact weight in any case.

      This is also why there is only one ramp and not a second, weaker one for small zoom levels. The
      near-black presence fill drawn zoomed out is a whole cell, not a glyph, and 4.2:1 across an area
      that size is plenty - the constraint that motivated weakening it simply does not apply there.
    -->
    <SolidColorBrush x:Key="MatrixColor1" po:Freeze="True">#D3DCE3</SolidColorBrush>
    <SolidColorBrush x:Key="MatrixColor2" po:Freeze="True">#B4C3CE</SolidColorBrush>
    <SolidColorBrush x:Key="MatrixColor3" po:Freeze="True">#93A8B7</SolidColorBrush>
    <SolidColorBrush x:Key="MatrixColor4" po:Freeze="True">#748C9E</SolidColorBrush>

    <!--
      Cycles. The one thing you actually hunt for in a DSM, and it overwrites every other cell colour,
      so it has to win the page. Warm against the cool ramp above, and kept off the red/green axis that
      the consumer/provider indicators use. The original mustard (#ffdb58) had neither the contrast nor
      the headroom for the highlight multiply.
    -->
    <SolidColorBrush x:Key="MatrixColorCycle" po:Freeze="True">#CF5C3C</SolidColorBrush>

    <!-- Consumer / provider indicator bars. Kept on their conventional green/blue, just less muddy. -->
    <SolidColorBrush x:Key="MatrixColorConsumer" po:Freeze="True">#6FA84B</SolidColorBrush>
    <SolidColorBrush x:Key="MatrixColorProvider" po:Freeze="True">#4A8DC4</SolidColorBrush>

    <!-- Search match and bookmark. Were pure #ff0000 / #00ff00; these stay loud but stop shouting. -->
    <SolidColorBrush x:Key="MatrixColorMatch" po:Freeze="True">#C2185B</SolidColorBrush>
    <SolidColorBrush x:Key="MatrixColorBookmark" po:Freeze="True">#7B3FA0</SolidColorBrush>

    <!--
      Misleading key: it used to paint the weight bar inside a cell, which is gone (see README.md in
      ThirdParty/DsmSuite). Its only remaining reader is the 1px separator before the selected pair in
      LegendView, so this is a rule colour, not a cell colour.
    -->
    <SolidColorBrush x:Key="CellWeightColor" po:Freeze="True">#37474F</SolidColorBrush>

    <!--
      Header height. 60 was sized for the element order alone; the column headers now carry the name too,
      and this is the width DrawText clips a rotated label at. 240 fits the longest assembly level label
      ("464 CSharpCodeAnalyst.CodeGraph" is roughly 230px in Segoe UI 14).

      This is the one number to turn if the headers feel too tall: labels are anchored at the top, so the
      element order stays readable at any height and only the tail of a long name is lost.
    -->
    <sys:Double x:Key="MatrixHeaderHeight">240</sys:Double>
</ResourceDictionary>
